recordings.rmk: Irritation calls from an adult Sedge Warbler.  The bird started to call as I walked along a small road running between groves of willow bushes. Lots of Sedge Warblers and Willow Warblers were in this habitat. As is normally the case with Sedge Warblers, simply by stopping at the location from where the calls are first made, provokes the caller to approach and become even more irritated. Even though I was standing at the roadside, the bird came very close, to within two metres, although always remaining within cover. Another similar recording, featuring a different adult, was recorded minutes later: XC332874

An excerpt from an adult Sedge Warbler that sang for at least a full hour. The delivery was fast and furious, a fact that I found remarkable given the date (1st August) at what is the end of the breeding season. The bird sang from a variety of perches along the edge of a reed-filled ditch. Breeding had occurred here and I assume the songster was the male. As is normal with Sedge Warbler, impersonations of other species are woven into the performance. In this clip (only slightly edited to remove wind noise as the morning was breezy and dull) the bird copies flight calls of Linnet (0:37), Swallow alarm calls (0:45 but becoming clearer over the next two seconds), Meadow Pipit's high-pitched anxiety notes (from 1:05 for the next seven seconds), Willow Warbler (six calls commencing at 1:16) and Meadow pipit flight calls (1:32 until the end of the clip).  Actual recordings of the species copied by the Sedge Warbler can be heard for Linnet at XC235375, Swallow at XC271037, Meadow Pipit at XC188715 and Willow Warbler at XC195135.

Reed Warbler's call is a raspy churr. In the background, Coots can be heard.

Song from a singing Sedge Warbler is often fast and chattering. Its rhythm recalls a busy typist, quickly and noisily hammering out a line of typing and then hitting the return key before resuming the staccato mechanical tapping. I know that the 'busy typist' analogy is rapidly disappearing from memory but for those old enough to remember the sound its likeness does strike a chord. In addition, Sedge Warblers like to mimic other bird voices. The mimicry applies to neighbours on the breeding grounds and also to sounds heard on the bird's travels. I have never been to Africa so I am oblivious to any copycat sounds from the winter quarters. However, the bird's memory is good and I have heard Sedge Warblers mimic European species that do not occur in areas where they breed. A hallmark of whatever is copied appears to be the angst of a sound. Hence, alarm notes are favourite imitations. The bird on the clip was singing from among young trees and reeds.  As well as its own compositions it draws extensively from the flight calls of Meadow Pipit, the alarm notes of Swallow and the twittering flight calls of Linnets. Imitations of Meadow Pipit are at 0:13, from 0:16 to the 20th second and at 1:32. For comparison, this is a real Meadow Pipit: XC247567. Swallow alarms are incorporated from 0:51 until I minute and 7 seconds and at 1:47. Here is the real thing: XC247566. Linnet calls feature strongly from 2:07 for almost the next 30 seconds. Here is the real thing: XC247565. Background species - not imitated! - are Skylark (faint but audible around 0:07); Raven 0:23 and 1:17; House Sparrow 1:17; Robin 1:25 and Rock Dove (wing whirr followed by cooing) from 2:29.
